+# API session sync
+
+This document describes the Hermes API-server session sync engine: how a
+desktop/mobile/web client attaches to a session over HTTP, receives history and
+live events, and resumes after any disconnect — including an API-server
+restart — without losing or duplicating events.
+
+## Goals
+
+- Re-open a session after app close/tab switch/device switch.
+- Receive current persisted history immediately.
+- Join a session while a run is already streaming and catch up on missed
+  deltas/tool events.
+- Keep more than one client attached without stealing events from the
+  initiating client.
+- Resume from a single opaque cursor via the SSE standard `Last-Event-ID`
+  mechanism — a browser `EventSource` reconnects correctly with zero client
+  bookkeeping.
+- Realtime delivery: events are pushed to subscribers when they are written,
+  not discovered on a polling timer.
+- Learn that an in-flight run died when the server restarted mid-turn.
+
+## Primary endpoint: session subscription SSE
+
+```http
+GET /api/sessions/{session_id}/subscribe
+Authorization: Bearer <API_SERVER_KEY>
+```
+
+For browser `EventSource`, where custom headers are awkward, query-token auth
+is also accepted:
+
+```http
+GET /api/sessions/{session_id}/subscribe?access_token=<API_SERVER_KEY>
+```
+
+The response is `text/event-stream`. The first event is always
+`session.snapshot`.
+
+Snapshot shape:
+
+```json
+{
+  "object": "hermes.session.snapshot",
+  "session_id": "api_...",
+  "session": { "id": "api_...", "title": "...", "message_count": 2, "...": "..." },
+  "messages": [
+    { "id": 1, "role": "user", "content": "...", "items": [...] },
+    { "id": 2, "role": "assistant", "content": "...", "items": [...] }
+  ],
+  "items": [
+    { "id": "msg:1", "type": "message", "role": "user", "content": "..." }
+  ],
+  "latest_event_cursor": "123",
+  "active_run": {
+    "object": "hermes.session.run",
+    "run_id": "run_...",
+    "session_id": "api_...",
+    "status": "running",
+    "last_seq": 4,
+    "draft": "partial assistant text",
+    "reasoning": "partial reasoning/tool progress text",
+    "tool_status": "terminal…"
+  },
+  "cursor": "v1:123:run_...:4"
+}
+```
+
+After the snapshot, the stream emits:
+
+1. **Durable session events** from `state.db` (`session.item.upserted`,
+   `session.ended`, `session.reopened`, `session.transcript.replaced`,
+   `response.completed`, …). These carry a global `cursor` field.
+2. **Replayable active-run events** from `response_store.db` (`run.started`,
+   `message.started`, `assistant.delta`, `tool.progress`, `tool.started`,
+   `tool.completed`, `assistant.completed`, `run.completed`, `done`,
+   `error`, `run.interrupted`). These carry a per-run integer `seq` field.
+3. **`run.switch`** when the session's latest run changes while the
+   subscription is open. The payload contains the new run snapshot; the
+   server resets the per-run replay to `seq 0` for the new run automatically.
+4. **`run.status`** when the active run's status changes without a
+   corresponding replayable event (for example a `/v1/sessions/{id}/halt`).
+   The payload contains the updated run snapshot.
+
+Example run event:
+
+```text
+id: v1:123:run_abc:3
+event: assistant.delta
+data: {"run_id":"run_abc","session_id":"api_...","seq":3,"message_id":"msg_...","delta":"hello"}
+```
+
+## Resume cursor
+
+Every SSE frame (including the snapshot) carries an `id:` field containing a
+composite resume token:
+
+```text
+v1:<session_event_cursor>:<run_id>:<run_seq>
+```
+
+- `session_event_cursor` — global durable-event cursor ("everything up to and
+  including this event has been delivered").
+- `run_id` / `run_seq` — the active run at that point and the last delivered
+  per-run sequence number. The run slot is empty when no run has been observed.
+
+The token is opaque to clients: store the most recent `id` (or let
+`EventSource` do it for you) and present it on reconnect. Tokens are NOT
+comparable across sessions.
+
+### Reconnecting
+
+Three ways to resume, in server-side precedence order:
+
+1. **`Last-Event-ID` header** — sent automatically by `EventSource` on
+   reconnect. Highest precedence: an auto-reconnect re-sends the original
+   (stale) query string, so the header must win over query params.
+2. **`?resume=<token>`** — explicit composite-token query param for clients
+   that manage reconnects themselves. Malformed tokens are a 400.
+3. **Legacy split params** — `?after=<session_event_cursor>` (alias
+   `cursor`) and `?run_after=<run_seq>` (alias `after_seq`), unchanged from
+   the original protocol.
+
+Semantics on resume:
+
+- Durable session events replay strictly after `session_event_cursor`.
+- If the token's `run_id` still matches the session's latest run, run events
+  replay strictly after `run_seq`.
+- If the session has moved on to a different run, the stored `run_seq` is
+  ignored and the new run replays from `seq 0` (a `run.switch` event tells the
+  client to reset).
+
+With no cursor at all, durable events start from the snapshot-time cursor (the
+snapshot already contains the persisted history, so nothing is duplicated) and
+the active run replays from `seq 0` (so a mid-run joiner sees the full
+in-progress turn).
+
+### Server-restart interruption
+
+If the API server restarts while a run is in flight, startup recovery marks
+the run `interrupted` and appends a synthetic `run.interrupted` event at
+`last_seq + 1` in the run's replay log. Consequences:
+
+- A client resuming from its pre-restart cursor replays `run.interrupted`
+  instead of waiting forever for more deltas.
+- A fresh subscriber sees `active_run.status == "interrupted"` in the
+  snapshot.
+
+## Realtime characteristics
+
+- **Push:** every event writer in the API-server process signals subscribers
+  when it commits (via an in-process per-session notifier; transcript writes
+  from the agent's own `SessionDB` instance are covered by a module-level
+  listener hook in `hermes_state`). Delivery latency is not bound to any
+  polling interval.
+- **Poll fallback (2s):** writes from *other processes* sharing the same
+  `state.db` (CLI, gateway) cannot signal this process; subscribers re-check
+  the durable stores every 2 seconds to pick those up.
+- **Keepalive:** after 30 seconds of silence the stream emits a
+  `: keepalive` comment so intermediaries don't drop the connection.
+
+## Starting work in a session
+
+Use the persisted session stream endpoint to start a turn:
+
+```http
+POST /api/sessions/{session_id}/chat/stream
+Content-Type: application/json
+Authorization: Bearer <API_SERVER_KEY>
+
+{"message":"do the task"}
+```
+
+The initiating client may consume that response directly, but it does not
+have to be the only consumer — the run's events are durably persisted and any
+other client receives them via `/subscribe`. The agent turn keeps running if
+the initiating client disconnects; the initiator can itself rejoin through
+`/subscribe` with its last cursor.
+
+Queue a follow-up turn while a run is active with
+`POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/queue`.
+
+For non-initiating clients:
+
+1. Connect to `/api/sessions/{session_id}/subscribe`.
+2. Render `session.snapshot.messages` immediately.
+3. If `session.snapshot.active_run.status` is `queued` or `running`, keep
+   rendering incoming `assistant.delta`/tool/run events.
+
+## Companion endpoints
+
+- `GET /api/sessions` — list sessions; each row includes lightweight live
+  state (`active`, `status`, `sync_state`, `active_run`).
+- `POST /api/sessions` — create an empty session.
+- `GET /api/sessions/{session_id}` — session metadata with live-state fields.
+- `GET /api/sessions/{session_id}/messages` — persisted message history only.
+- `GET /v1/sessions/{session_id}/items` — stable item projection.
+- `GET /v1/sessions/{session_id}/events?after=<cursor>` — durable
+  session-event replay only (single poll, not streaming).
+- `GET /v1/runs/{run_id}` — run status polling, including
+  `waiting_for_approval` with the pending approval request payload; respond
+  via `POST /v1/runs/{run_id}/approval`. (The former
+  `GET /v1/runs/{run_id}/events` single-consumer SSE stream was removed; run
+  events are observed durably via `/subscribe`.)
+
+## Client rendering notes
+
+- Treat `messages` in `session.snapshot` as the authoritative persisted
+  transcript at attach time.
+- Treat `items` as the normalized render model for
+  message/tool-call/tool-result display.
+- Accumulate `assistant.delta` events by `message_id` for the current
+  in-progress assistant draft.
+- On `assistant.completed`, replace the draft with the completed content.
+- On `run.completed`, reconcile with `messages` in that payload if present;
+  Hermes includes the interleaved assistant/tool transcript for the completed
+  turn when available.
+- On `run.interrupted` or a `run.status` transition to a terminal state,
+  stop rendering the run as live.
+- Tool events may arrive as both renderable run events (`tool.progress`,
+  `tool.started`, `tool.completed`) and durable item upserts
+  (`session.item.upserted`) depending on the path. Use stable item ids and
+  tool_call ids to de-dupe.
+
+## Capability discovery
+
+`GET /v1/capabilities` advertises:
+
+- `features.session_subscribe_sse: true`
+- `features.session_sync_resume: true` — composite `id:` cursors +
+  `Last-Event-ID`/`?resume=` reconnects.
+- `endpoints.session_subscribe`
+
+## Implementation pointers
+
+- API-server adapter: `gateway/platforms/api_server.py`
+  - `SessionSyncNotifier` — per-session push wakeup fanout.
+  - `_encode_sync_cursor` / `_parse_sync_cursor` — composite token codec.
+  - `_handle_session_subscribe` — snapshot + resumable live SSE.
+  - `_handle_session_chat_stream` — persists replayable per-run events into
+    `ResponseStore.session_run_events`.
+  - `_record_live_tool_session_item` — publishes provisional tool call/result
+    item upserts into `SessionDB.session_events`.
+  - `ResponseStore.mark_incomplete_session_runs_interrupted` — startup
+    recovery + synthetic `run.interrupted` replay events.
+- Durable stores:
+  - `hermes_state.py` / `SessionDB.session_events` for session items and
+    global cursor-based sync; `register_session_event_listener` is the
+    module-level write hook the notifier attaches to.
+  - `ResponseStore.session_runs` / `session_run_events` in
+    `response_store.db` for per-run assistant deltas and lifecycle replay.
+
+## Verified behavior
+
+Regression coverage:
+
+- `tests/gateway/test_session_sync.py` — composite cursors, `Last-Event-ID`
+  reconnects, legacy params, multi-client fanout, push-beats-poll latency,
+  cross-thread/instance wakeups, restart interruption visibility,
+  join-in-progress and `run.switch`.
+- `tests/gateway/test_session_api.py` — snapshot/replay basics, chat-stream
+  run persistence, restart recovery of the run store.
+- `tests/test_hermes_state.py::TestSessionEventListeners` — the module-level
+  write hook.
+
+```bash
+uv run --extra dev --extra messaging python -m pytest \
+  tests/gateway/test_session_sync.py tests/gateway/test_session_api.py \
+  tests/test_hermes_state.py -q -o addopts=
+```
